name: N-Octyloctan-1-amine
Reason: 1,1'-Octadodecanamine has a melting point of 10.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The basic unit for our comparison will be octane, which has a melting point of -11.2°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of two additional methyl groups, which increase the molecular weight and van der Waals interactions, leading to a higher melting point. Additionally, the amine group can participate in hydrogen bonding, which can further contribute to the melting point.
